ess charging<ref name=\"Official website: specifications />\n| input        = \n| display      = {{convert|4.7|in|mm|abbr=on}} [[Retina display|Retina HD display]] with [[IPS panel|IPS]] technology, 1334 \u00d7 750 pixel resolution (326 [[pixels per inch|ppi]]), 1400:1 contrast ratio (typical), 625&nbsp;cd/m\u00b2 max. brightness (typical), with dual-ion exchange-strengthened glass and {{nowrap|[[Force Touch|Haptic Touch]]}}<ref name=\"Official website: specifications />\n| ext_display  = \n| rear_camera  = 12MP, f/1.8 aperture, optical image stabilization, True Tone flash, autofocus<br />4K video recording at 24, 30, or 60 fps<br />1080p HD video recording at 30 or 60 fps<br />720p HD video recording at 30 fps<br />Cinematic video stabilization (4K, 1080p, and 720p)<br />Slo\u2011mo video support for 1080p at 120 or 240 fps<br />Portrait mode, Portrait lighting, and Smart HDR\n| front_camera = \n| sound        = Stereo speakers\n| connectivity = [[Lightning (connector)|Lightning]] connector<br />Wi-Fi 6 ([[802.11ax]])<br>[[Bluetooth]] 5.0\n| other        = [[IP Code|IP67]] IEC standard 60529 (splash, water, and dust resistant)\n| sar          = \n| hac          = M3, T4\n| website      = {{URL|www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n| references   = \n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' is a [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is part of the 13th generation of the [[iPhone]], alongside the [[iPhone 11]] and [[iPhone 11 Pro]] models. Announced on April 15, 2020, the iPhone SE serves as a successor to both the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] and the [[iPhone 8]].\n\nSimilar to the first-generation SE (which shared the dimensions and form factor of the [[iPhone 5S]] but used the processor and camera of the newer [[iPhone 6S]]), the second-generation SE is a new model of a previous iPhone form factor (specifically, the iPhone 8) with hardware components from the iPhone 11 lineup (including the [[Apple A13]] processor), retaining a physical home button with [[Touch ID]] rather than the [[iPhone X]] form factor (with an edge-to-edge display, gesture navigation, and [[Face ID]]).\n\nWith a starting price of $399 in the United States, the iPhone SE is the cheapest iPhone Apple makes, significantly undercutting the iPhone 11 models. Pre-orders of the SE began on April 17, 2020, while deliveries are due to commence on April 24.\n\n== History ==\nA successor to the first-generation iPhone SE has been rumored since 2017, a year after the device was released.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/22/iphone-se-2-release-date-first-half-2018/ |title = iPhone SE 2 Again Rumored to Launch in First Half of 2018 |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 }}</ref> The phone also has other rumored names: '''iPhone SE 2 / iPhone SE2''', '''iPhone''', '''iPhone SE (2020)''', and closer to its launch, '''iPhone 9''', due to design similarities with the iPhone 8.\n\nIn March 2020, cases for the phone were reportedly being shipped to [[Best Buy]],<ref name=\"9to5mac\">{{Cite web |url = https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |title = iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date |last = Miller |first = Chance |date = March 30, 2020 |accessdate = April 3, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200403181051/https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |archive-date = April 3, 2020 |url-status = live }}</ref> showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body and a single camera lens.<ref name=\"9to5mac\" /> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for the iPhone SE were also listed on the online [[Apple Store]], cross-compatible with the iPhone 8 and iPhone 7. However, references to the iPhone SE were quickly removed.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se |title = iPhone 9 will be called iPhone SE and could launch soon (Update) |website = Tom's Guide |accessdate = April 3, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"9to5mac\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe iPhone SE features a design with an aluminum frame, and its front and back are made out of glass. The phone's dimensions are identical to that of the iPhone 8, and the external design is the same except for a centered Apple logo and no iPhone branding. It features bezels on the top and bottom of the front and a home button integrated with second-generation [[Touch ID]].<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE 2020: Everything We Know |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112853/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |archive-date = August 5, 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone SE is available in three colors \u2014 white, black,<!-- colors are not proper nouns --> and a [[Product Red]] edition.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications /> Where this iPhone does deviate from the iPhone 8's design is with respect to the white model. Unlike the silver iPhone 8 (and all prior silver iPhones since the [[iPhone 5]]), the white iPhone SE features black bezels like the black models and red models, in line with the color schemes of the [[iPhone 11]] and [[iPhone XR]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#1F2020\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F9F6EF\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#BA0C2E\"  |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the Apple A13 Bionic system-on-chip (SoC) with an [[Apple motion coprocessors|M13 motion coprocessor]] and a third-generation neural engine. It is available in three internal storage configurations; 64&nbsp;GB, 128&nbsp;GB and 256&nbsp;GB.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> The SE has a rating of IP67 under [[IP Code|IEC standard 60529]] for dust and water resistance.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> \nThe [[ultra-wideband]] hardware on the iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro is not included due to the lack of the Apple U1 chip.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/04/15/apples-new-iphone-se-doesnt-have-a-u1-ultra-wideband-chip|title=Apple's new iPhone SE doesn't have a U1 Ultra Wideband chip|website=appleinsider|last=Peterson|first=Mike|date=April 15, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n==== Display ====\nThe iPhone SE features the same Retina HD display found on the iPhone 8, with True Tone and wide color gamut. It can play [[HDR10]] and [[Dolby Vision]] content despite not having an HDR-ready display, done by down-converting the HDR content to fit the display while still having some enhancements to dynamic range, contrast, and wide color gamut compared to [[standard-dynamic-range video|standard]] content. [[Force Touch|3D Touch]] has been replaced with Haptic Touch.\n\n==== Camera ====\nThe iPhone SE features a single 12 MP rear camera similar to the wide camera of iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro. The camera has a <!-- MOS:NOSYMBOLS -->f/1.8 aperture, autofocus, optical image stabilization, and a quad-LED True Tone flash. It is capable of recording 4K video at 24&nbsp;fps, 30&nbsp;fps, or 60&nbsp;fps, 1080p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps or 60&nbsp;fps, or 720p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps. The phone can also take panoramas up to 63&nbsp;MP, and is capable of shooting photos in burst mode. Compared to the iPhone 8, the iPhone SE adds extended dynamic range for video up to 30 fps and Stereo recording. The SE also adopts \"QuickTake\" from the 11 and 11 Pro, which allows the user to long-press the shutter button to take a video.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nThe front camera is 7&nbsp;MP with f/2.2 aperture and autofocus, capable of shooting 1080p HD video at 30 fps.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nBoth the front and rear cameras of the iPhone SE support Smart HDR, Portrait mode and Portrait Lighting.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> Unlike the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro, the iPhone SE does not support Night Mode, possibly due to being based on the [[iPhone XR]] single-camera system.\n\n===Software===\nThe iPhone SE ships with [[iOS]] [[iOS 13|13]] and supports [[Apple Pay]].<!-- Apple Card is implicit with Apple Pay. --><ref name=\"Official website: specifications />\n\n== Timeline of iPhone models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|iPhone SE (2020)}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2nd generation iPhone SE|its predecessor|iPhone SE (1st generation)|the general use of the term ''iPhone SE''|iPhone SE (disambiguation)}}\n<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=iPhone SE (2020)|2=Talk:IPhone SE (2nd generation)#Requested move 16 April 2020 }}\n{{Under construction}}\n</noinclude>\n{{pp-move|small=yes}}\n{{short description|thirteenth-generation smartphone designed and sold by Apple Inc}}\n{{lowercase title}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name         = iPhone SE\n| codename     = \n| logo         = IPhone SE (2nd generation) wordmark.svg\n| logosize     = <!-- include \"px\" - Uses users default image size if omitted -->\n| image        = IPhone SE (2nd generation) white vector.svg\n| imagesize    = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = iPhone SE in white, with black bezel\n| brand        = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = \n| slogan       = ''Lots to love. Less to spend.''<ref name=\"Official webpage\" >{{Cite web |url = https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE |website = Apple |langu