sistant)\n| sar          = \n| hac          = M3, T4\n| website      = {{URL|www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n| references   = \n}}\n{{iPhone models}}\nThe '''second-generation iPhone SE''' is a [[smartphone]] designed, developed, and marketed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is part of the 13th generation of the [[iPhone]], alongside the [[iPhone 11]], [[IPhone 11 Pro|iPhone 11 Pro, and iPhone 11 Pro Max]]. Announced on April 15, 2020 with pre-orders opened two days later, the iPhone SE serves as a successor to both the [[iPhone SE (1st generation)|first-generation iPhone SE]] and the [[iPhone 8]].\n\nSimilarly to the original SE (which shared the dimensions and form factor of the [[iPhone 5]] and [[iPhone 5S]] but contained hardware similar to the larger [[iPhone 6S]]), the new SE is a new model of a previous iPhone form factor (specifically, the iPhone 8) with hardware components from the current iPhone 11 lineup (including the [[Apple A13]] processor), retaining a physical home button with [[Touch ID]] rather than the [[iPhone X]] form factor (with an edge-to-edge display, gesture navigation, and [[Face ID]]).\n\n== History ==\nA successor to the first-generation iPhone SE has been rumored since 2017, a year after the device was released.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/2017/11/22/iphone-se-2-release-date-first-half-2018/ |title = iPhone SE 2 Again Rumored to Launch in First Half of 2018 |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 }}</ref> The phone also has other rumored names: '''iPhone SE 2 / iPhone SE2''', '''iPhone''', '''iPhone SE (2020)''', and closer to its launch, '''iPhone 9''', due to design similarities with the iPhone 8.\n\nIn March 2020, cases for the phone were reportedly being shipped to [[Best Buy]],<ref name=\"9to5mac\">{{Cite web |url = https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |title = iPhone 9 case inventory arriving at Best Buy, other retailers with April 5 merchandising date |last = Miller |first = Chance |date = March 30, 2020 |accessdate = April 3, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200403181051/https://9to5mac.com/2020/03/30/iphone-9-case-inventory-best-buy/ |archive-date = April 3, 2020 |url-status = live }}</ref> showing an iPhone with an [[iPhone 8]]-sized body and a single camera lens.<ref name=\"9to5mac\" /> [[Belkin]] screen protectors for the iPhone SE were also listed on the online [[Apple Store]], cross-compatible with the iPhone 8 and iPhone 7. However, references to the iPhone SE were quickly removed.<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.tomsguide.com/news/apple-iphone-9-will-be-the-new-iphone-se |title = iPhone 9 will be called iPhone SE and could launch soon (Update) |website = Tom's Guide |accessdate = April 3, 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"9to5mac\" />\n\n== Design ==\nThe iPhone SE features a design with an aluminum frame, and its front and back are made out of glass. The phone's dimensions are identical to that of the iPhone 8, and the external design is the same except for a centered Apple logo and no iPhone branding. It features bezels on the top and bottom of the front and a home button integrated with second-generation [[Touch ID]].<ref>{{Cite web |url = https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |title = iPhone SE 2020: Everything We Know |website = MacRumors |language = en |access-date = April 15, 2020 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180805112853/https://www.macrumors.com/roundup/iphone-se/ |archive-date = August 5, 2018 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nThe iPhone SE is available in three colors \u2014 white, black,<!-- colors are not proper nouns --> and a [[Product Red]] edition.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications /> Where this iPhone does deviate from the iPhone 8's design is with respect to the white model. Unlike the silver iPhone 8 (and all prior silver iPhones since the [[iPhone 5]]), the white iPhone SE features black bezels like the black models and red models, in line with the color schemes of the [[iPhone 11]] and [[iPhone XR]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Color !!Name      <!-- hex codes from product selection page -->\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#1F2020\"| ||Black \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"F9F6EF\" |  ||White \n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#BA0C2E\"  |  ||Product Red\n|}\n\n== Specifications ==\n\n===Hardware===\nThe iPhone SE incorporates the Apple A13 Bionic system-on-chip (SoC) with an [[Apple motion coprocessors|M13 motion coprocessor]] and a third-generation neural engine. It is available in three internal storage configurations; 64&nbsp;GB, 128&nbsp;GB and 256&nbsp;GB.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> The SE has a rating of IP67 under [[IP Code|IEC standard 60529]] for dust and water resistance.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> \nThe [[ultra-wideband]] hardware on the iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro is not included due to the lack of the Apple U1 chip.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/20/04/15/apples-new-iphone-se-doesnt-have-a-u1-ultra-wideband-chip|title=Apple's new iPhone SE doesn't have a U1 Ultra Wideband chip|website=appleinsider|last=Peterson|first=Mike|date=April 15, 2020|access-date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n==== Display ====\nThe iPhone SE features the same Retina HD display found on the iPhone 8, with True Tone and wide color gamut. It can play [[HDR10]] and [[Dolby Vision]] content despite not having an HDR-ready display, done by down-converting the HDR content to fit the display while still having some enhancements to dynamic range, contrast, and wide color gamut compared to [[standard-dynamic-range video|standard]] content. [[Force Touch|3D Touch]] has been replaced with Haptic Touch.\n\n==== Camera ====\nThe iPhone SE features a single 12 MP rear camera similar to the wide camera of iPhone 11 and iPhone 11 Pro. The camera has a <!-- MOS:NOSYMBOLS -->f/1.8 aperture, autofocus, optical image stabilization, and a quad-LED True Tone flash. It is capable of recording 4K video at 24&nbsp;fps, 30&nbsp;fps, or 60&nbsp;fps, 1080p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps or 60&nbsp;fps, or 720p HD video at 30&nbsp;fps. The phone can also take panoramas up to 63&nbsp;MP, and is capable of shooting photos in burst mode. Compared to the iPhone 8, the iPhone SE adds extended dynamic range for video up to 30 fps and Stereo recording. The SE also adopts \"QuickTake\" from the 11 and 11 Pro, which allows the user to long-press the shutter button to take a video.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nThe front camera is 7&nbsp;MP with f/2.2 aperture and autofocus, capable of shooting 1080p HD video at 30 fps.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" />\n\nBoth the front and rear cameras of the iPhone SE support Smart HDR, Portrait mode and Portrait Lighting.<ref name=\"Official website: specifications\" /> Unlike the iPhone 11 and 11 Pro, the iPhone SE does not support Night Mode, possibly due to being based on the [[iPhone XR]] single-camera system.\n\n===Software===\nThe iPhone SE ships with [[iOS]] [[iOS 13|13]] and supports [[Apple Pay]].<!-- Apple Card is implicit with Apple Pay. --><ref name=\"Official website: specifications />\n\n== Timeline of iPhone models ==\n{{Timeline of iPhone models}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|iPhone SE (2020)}}\n* {{Official site|https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/}}\n\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc. hardware}}\n{{Apple}}\n[[Category:IPhone|*]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2020]]\n[[Category:iOS]]\n[[Category:Mobile phones introduced in 2020]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications]]\n", "name_user": "ReverseLevity", "label": "safe", "comment": "Tidied up lead; removed redundant references to iPhone 11 Pro Max and iPhone 5, added the fact that it's the entry level iPhone", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone_SE_(2nd_generation)"}
{"title_page": "Counter-based random number generator (CBRNG)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=August 2016}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2016}}\n{{one source|date=August 2016}}\n}}\n'''Counter-Based Random Number Generation''' ('''CBRNG''') is a technique for creating a [[pseudorandom number generator]] using only an integer counter as the internal state of the generator.\n\nMost pseudorandom generators rely on some type of internal state and a function that updates the state. Each value of the internal state is then mapped to one pseudorandom sample. Normally the [[Transition system|state transition function]] is complicated and the function mapping state to a sample is simple. In the case of counter-based generators the internal state is just an integer counter. The state transition function is an increment by one. The complexity comes in the map from the state to the random sample.\n\nBecause the state is just a counter it is trivial to split [[random number generation]] between parallel processors without overlap. Skip-a-head and rewind in the stream of generated random numbers also become trivial ''O''(1) operations. It is easy to organize different numbers of parallel processors to generate the same sequence of pseudorandom numbers.\n\nThe technique was proposed by a group at [[D. E. Shaw Research]]<ref>{{Cite conference|title = Parallel random numbers: as easy as 1, 2, 3|last = Salmon|first = John|date = 2011|book-title = Proceedings of 2011 International Conference for High Performance Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis, Article No. 16|doi = 10.1145/2063384.2063405|last2 = Moraes|first2 = Mark|last3 = Dror|first3 = Ron|last4 = Shaw|first4 = David}}</ref> In addition to the general technique, specific generators named [[ARS (Random Number Generator)|ARS]], [[Threefry]], and [[Philox]] were proposed as examples. Code implementing the generators is available in a library{{Cite web|url=https://www.deshawresearch.com/resources_random123.html|title=Random123}}. The ARS-5 generator is included in recent versions of the Intel [[Math Kernel Library]] and has excellent performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/new-counter-based-random-number-generators-in-intel-math-kernel-library |title=New counter-based Random Number Generators in Intel\u00ae Math Kernel Library |last1=Fedorov |first1=Gennady |last2=Gladkov |first2=Eugeny |date=2015 |publisher=Intel |access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Variations of Philox are the fastest generators on GPUs that pass both [[TestU01]] and the Ising test.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Manssen |first=M. |last2=Weigel |first2=M|last3=Hartmann |first3=A.K. |date=August 2012 |title=Random number generators for massively parallel simulations on GPU |url= |journal= The European Physical Journal Special Topics|volume=210 |issue=1 |pages=53\u201371 |doi=10.1140/epjst/e2012-01637-8 |arxiv=1204.6193 |bibcode=2012EPJST.210...53M }}</ref>\n\n\u201cSquares: A Fast Counter-Based RNG\u201d was recently published<ref name=\"mswsrngpaper\">{{cite arXiv\n| last=Widynski | first=Bernard\n| arxiv=2004.06278 \n| title=Squares: A Fast Counter-Based RNG\n| date=April 2020}}</ref>. [[John von Neumann]]\u2019s [[middle-square method | middle square]] is used for randomization.  Several rounds are applied to a counter to produce a random output.  This RNG passes stringent tests of randomness and may the fastest counter-based generator.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pseudorandom number generators]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{cleanup reorganize|date=August 2016}}\n{{more footnotes|date=August 2016}}\n{{one source|date=August 2016}}\n}}\n'''Counter-Based Random Number Generation''' ('''CBRNG''') is a technique for creating a [[pseudorandom number generator]] using only an integer counter as the internal state of the generator.\n\nMost pseudorandom generators rely on some type of internal state and a function that updates the state. Each value of the internal state is then mapped to one pseudorandom sample. Normally the [[Transition system|state transition function]] is complicated and the function mapping state to a sample is simple. In the case of counter-based generators the internal state is just an integer counter. The state transition function is an increment by one. The complexity comes in the map from the state to the random sample.\n\nBecause the state is just a counter it is trivial to split [[random number generation]] between parallel processors without overlap. Skip-a-head and rewind in the stream of generated random numbers also become trivial ''O''(1) operations. It is easy to organize different numbers of parallel processors to generate the same sequence of pseudorandom numbers.\n\nThe technique was proposed by a group at [[D. E. Shaw Research]]<ref>{{Cite conference|title = Parallel random numbers: as easy as 1, 2, 3|last = Salmon|first = John|date = 2011|book-title = Proceedings of 2011 International Conference for High Performance Computing, Networking, Storage and Analysis, Article No. 16|doi = 10.1145/2063384.2063405|last2 = Moraes|first2 = Mark|last3 = Dror|first3 = Ron|last4 = Shaw|first4 = David}}</ref> In addition to the general technique, specific generators named [[ARS (Random Number Generator)|ARS]], [[Threefry]], and [[Philox]] were proposed as examples. Code implementing the generators is available in a library{{Cite web|url=https://www.deshawresearch.com/resources_random123.html|title=Random123}}. The ARS-5 generator is included in recent versions of the Intel [[Math Kernel Library]] and has excellent performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/new-counter-based-random-number-generators-in-intel-math-kernel-library |title=New counter-based Random Number Generators in Intel\u00ae Math Kernel Library |last1=Fedorov |first1=Gennady |last2=Gladkov |first2=Eugeny |date=2015 |publisher=Intel |access-date=August 22, 2016}}</ref> Variations of Philox are the fastest generators on GPUs that pass both [[TestU01]] and the Ising test.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Manssen |first=M. |last2=Weigel |first2=M|last3=Hartmann |first3=A.K. |date=August 2012 |title=Random number generators for massively parallel simulations on GPU |url= |journal= The European Physical Journal Special Topics|volume=210 |issue=1 |pages=53\u201371 |doi=10.1140/epjst/e2012-01637-8 |arxiv=1204.6193 |bibcode=2012EPJST.210...53M }}</ref>\n\n\u201cSquares: A Fast Counter-Based RNG\u201d was recently published<ref name=\"mswsrngpaper\">{{cite arXiv\n| last=Widynski | first=Bernard\n| arxiv=2004.06278 \n| title=Squares: A Fast Counter-Based RNG\n| date=April 2020}}</ref>.  Several rounds of [[John von Neumann]]\u2019s [[middle-square method | middle-square transformation]] are applied to a counter to produce a random output.  This RNG passes stringent tests of randomness and may the fastest counter-based generator.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Pseudorandom number generators]]\n", "name_user": "ItsMutual", "label": "safe", "comment": "Revised wording for squares", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Counter-based_random_number_generator_(CBRNG)"}
{"title_page": "Centrosymmetric matrix", "text_new": "[[File:Matrix symmetry qtl4.svg|thumb|Symmetry pattern of a centrosymmetric 5\u00d75 matrix]]\nIn [[mathematics]], especially in [[linear algebra]] and [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix theory]], a '''centrosymmetric matrix''' is a [[matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] which is symmetric about its center. More precisely, an ''n'' \u00d7 ''n'' matrix ''A'' = [ ''A''<sub>i,j</sub> ] is centrosymmetric when its entries satisfy\n\n:''A''<sub>i,j</sub> = ''A''<sub>n\u2212i+1,n\u2212j+1</sub> for 1 \u2264 i,j \u2264 n.\n\nIf ''J'' denotes the ''n'' \u00d7 ''n'' matrix with 1 on the counterdiagonal and 0 elsewhere (that is, ''J''<sub>i,n+1-i</sub> = 1; ''J''<sub>i,j</sub> = 0 if j \u2260 n+1-i), then a matrix ''A'' is centrosymmetric if and only if ''AJ = JA''.  The matrix ''J'' is sometimes referred to as the [[exchange matrix]].\n\n==Examples==\n\n* All 2\u00d72 centrosymmetric matrices have the form\n:<math> \\begin{bmatrix} a & b \\\\ b & a \\end{bmatrix}. </math>\n\n* All 3\u00d73 centrosymmetric matrices have the form\n:<math> \\begin{bmatrix} a & b & c \\\\ d & e & d \\\\ c & b & a \\end{bmatrix}. </math>\n\n* [[Symmetric matrix|Symmetric]] [[Toeplitz matrix|Toeplitz]] matrices are centrosymmetric.\n\n==Algebraic structure and properties==\n*If ''A'' and ''B'' are centrosymmetric matrices over a given [[field (mathematics)|field]] ''F'', then so are ''A+B'' and ''cA'' for any ''c'' in ''F''. In addition, the [[matrix product]] ''AB'' is centrosymmetric, since ''JAB = AJB = ABJ''. Since the [[identity matrix]] is also centrosymmetric, it follows that the set of ''n \u00d7 n'' centrosymmetric matrices over ''F'' is a subalgebra of the [[associative algebra]] of all ''n \u00d7 n'' matrices.\n*If ''A'' is a centrosymmetric matrix with an ''m''-dimensional eigenbasis, then its ''m'' eigenvectors can each be chosen so that they satisfy either ''x=Jx'' or ''x=-Jx''.\n*If ''A'' is a centrosymmetric matrix with distinct eigenvalues, then the matrices that commute with ''A'' must be centrosymmetric.<ref name=acta/>\n\n==Related structures==\nAn ''n \u00d7 n'' matrix ''A'' is said to be ''skew-centrosymmetric'' if its entries satisfy ''A''<sub>i,j</sub> = -''A''<sub>n\u2212i+1,n\u2212j+1</sub> for 1 \u2264 i,j \u2264 n. Equivalently, ''A'' is skew-centrosymmetric if ''AJ = -JA'', where ''J'' is the exchange matrix defined above.\n\nThe centrosymmetric relation ''AJ = JA'' lends itself to a natural generalization, where ''J'' is replaced with an [[involutory matrix]] ''K'' (i.e., ''K<sup>2</sup> = I'')<ref name=\"AA\">{{Cite journal|doi=10.1016/0024-3795(73)90049-9|first=Alan |last=Andrew|title= Eigenvectors of certain matrices|journal= Linear Algebra Appl.| volume= 7 |year=1973|issue=2|pages=151\u2013162}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"simax0\">{{cite journal\n |last1=Tao \n |first1=David\n |last2=Yasuda \n |first2=Mark\n |title=A spectral characterization of generalized real symmetric centrosymmetric and generalized real symmetric skew-centrosymmetric matrices \n |journal=SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl. \n |volume=23 \n |issue=3 \n |pages=885\u2013895 \n |year=2002 \n |doi=10.1137/S0895479801386730 \n|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1236140/files/article.pdf \n }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"laa\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.laa.2003.07.013|first=W. F.|last= Trench|title= Characterization and properties of matrices with generalized symmetry or skew symmetry|journal=Linear Algebra Appl. |volume=377 |year=2004|pages=207\u2013218}}</ref> or, more generally, a matrix ''K'' satisfying ''K<sup>m</sup> = I'' for an integer ''m > 1''.<ref name=acta>{{cite journal | last = Yasuda | first = Mark | title = Some properties of commuting and anti-commuting m-involutions | journal = Acta Mathematica Scientia | volume = 32 | issue = 2 | pages = 631\u2013644 | year = 2012| doi = 10.1016/S0252-9602(12)60044-7}}</ref>  The inverse problem for the commutation relation ''AK = KA'' of identifying all involutory ''K'' that commute with a fixed matrix ''A'', has also been studied.<ref name=acta/>\n\n[[Symmetric matrix|Symmetric]] centrosymmetric matrices are sometimes called [[bisymmetric matrix|bisymmetric matrices]].  When the [[Field (mathematics)|ground field]] is the field of [[real numbers]], it has been shown that bisymmetric matrices are precisely those symmetric matrices whose [[eigenvalues]] remain the same aside from possible sign changes following  pre or post multiplication by the exchange matrix.<ref name = \"simax0\"/>  A similar result holds for Hermitian centrosymmetric and skew-centrosymmetric matrices.<ref name=\"simax1\">{{cite journal | last = Yasuda | first = Mark | title = A Spectral Characterization of Hermitian Centrosymmetric and Hermitian Skew-Centrosymmetric K-Matrices | journal = SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl. | volume = 25 | issue = 3 | pages = 601\u2013605 | year = 2003 | doi = 10.1137/S0895479802418835}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Thomas|last=Muir|author-link=Thomas Muir (mathematician)|year=1960|title=A Treatise on the Theory of Determinants|url=https://archive.org/details/treatiseontheory0000muir|url-access=registration|publisher=Dover|page=[https://archive.org/details/treatiseontheory0000muir/page/19 19]|isbn= 0-486-60670-8}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2307/2323222|first=James R. |last=Weaver|title= Centrosymmetric (cross-symmetric) matrices, their basic properties, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors|journal=American Mathematical Monthly|volume=92|issue=10|year=1985|pages=711\u2013717|jstor=2323222 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/CentrosymmetricMatrix.html Centrosymmetric matrix] on [[MathWorld]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Centrosymmetric Matrix}}\n[[Category:Linear algebra]]\n[[Category:Matrices]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Matrix symmetry qtl4.svg|thumb|Symmetry pattern of a centrosymmetric 5\u00d75 matrix]]\nIn [[mathematics]], especially in [[linear algebra]] and [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix theory]], a '''centrosymmetric matrix''' is a [[matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] which is symmetric about its center. More precisely, an ''n'' \u00d7 ''n'' matrix ''A'' = [ ''A''<sub>i,j</sub> ] is centrosymmetric when its entries satisfy\n\n:''A''<sub>i,j</sub> = ''A''<sub>n\u2212i+1,n\u2212j+1</sub> for 1 \u2264 i,j \u2264 n.\n\nIf ''J'' denotes the ''n'' \u00d7 ''n'' matrix with 1 on the counterdiagonal and 0 elsewhere (that is, ''J''<sub>i,n+1-i</sub> = 1; ''J''<sub>i,j</sub> = 0 if j \u2260 n+1-i), then a matrix ''A'' is centrosymmetric if and only if ''AJ = JA''.  The matrix ''J'' is sometimes referred to as the [[exchange matrix]].\n\n==Examples==\n\n* All 2\u00d72 centrosymmetric matrices have the form\n:<math> \\begin{bmatrix} a & b \\\\ b & a \\end{bmatrix}. </math>\n\n* All 3\u00d73 centrosymmetric matrices have the form\n:<math> \\begin{bmatrix} a & b & c \\\\ d & e & d \\\\ c & b & a \\end{bmatrix}. </math>\n\n* [[Symmetric matrix|Symmetric]] [[Toeplitz matrix|Toeplitz]] matrices are centrosymmetric.\n\n==Algebraic structure and properties==\n*If ''A'' and ''B'' are centrosymmetric matrices over a given [[field (mathematics)|field]] ''F'', then so are ''A+B'' and ''cA'' for any ''c'' in ''F''. In addition, the [[matrix product]] ''AB'' is centrosymmetric, since ''JAB = AJB = ABJ''. Since the [[identity matrix]] is also centrosymmetric, it follows that the set of ''n \u00d7 n'' centrosymmetric matrices over ''F'' is a subalgebra of the [[associative algebra]] of all ''n \u00d7 n'' matrices.\n*If ''A'' is a centrosymmetric matrix with an ''m''-dimensional eigenbasis, then its ''m'' eigenvectors can each be chosen so that they satisfy either ''x=Jx'' or ''x=-Jx''.\n*If ''A'' is a centrosymmetric matrix with distinct eigenvalues, then the matrices that commute with ''A'' must be centrosymmetric.<ref name=acta/>\n\n==Related structures==\nAn ''n \u00d7 n'' matrix ''A'' is said to be ''skew-centrosymmetric'' if its entries satisfy ''A''<sub>i,j</sub> = -''A''<sub>n\u2212i+1,n\u2212j+1</sub> for 1 \u2264 i,j \u2264 n. Equivalently, ''A'' is skew-centrosymmetric if ''AJ = -JA'', where ''J'' is the exchange matrix defined above.\n\nThe centrosymmetric relation ''AJ = JA'' lends itself to a natural generalization, where ''J'' is replaced with an [[involutory matrix]] ''K'' (i.e., ''K<sup>2</sup> = I'')<ref name=\"AA\">{{Cite journal|doi=10.1016/0024-3795(73)90049-9|first=A. |last=Andrew|title= Eigenvectors of certain matrices|journal= Linear Algebra Appl.| volume= 7 |year=1973|issue=2|pages=151\u2013162}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"simax0\">{{cite journal\n |last1=Tao \n |first1=D. \n |last2=Yasuda \n |first2=M. \n |title=A spectral characterization of generalized real symmetric centrosymmetric and generalized real symmetric skew-centrosymmetric matrices \n |journal=SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl. \n |volume=23 \n |issue=3 \n |pages=885\u2013895 \n |year=2002 \n |doi=10.1137/S0895479801386730 \n|url=https://zenodo.org/record/1236140/files/article.pdf \n }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"laa\">{{cite journal|doi=10.1016/j.laa.2003.07.013|first=W. F.|last= Trench|title= Characterization and properties of matrices with generalized symmetry or skew symmetry|journal=Linear Algebra Appl. |volume=377 |year=2004|pages=207\u2013218}}</ref> or, more generally, a matrix ''K'' satisfying ''K<sup>m</sup> = I'' for an integer ''m > 1''.<ref name=acta>{{cite journal | last = Yasuda | first = M. | title = Some properties of commuting and anti-commuting m-involutions | journal = Acta Mathematica Scientia | volume = 32 | issue = 2 | pages = 631\u2013644 | year = 2012| doi = 10.1016/S0252-9602(12)60044-7}}</ref>  The inverse problem for the commutation relation ''AK = KA'' of identifying all involutory ''K'' that commute with a fixed matrix ''A'', has also been studied.<ref name=acta/>\n\n[[Symmetric matrix|Symmetric]] centrosymmetric matrices are sometimes called [[bisymmetric matrix|bisymmetric matrices]].  When the [[Field (mathematics)|ground field]] is the field of [[real numbers]], it has been shown that bisymmetric matrices are precisely those symmetric matrices whose [[eigenvalues]] remain the same aside from possible sign changes following  pre or post multiplication by the exchange matrix.<ref name = \"simax0\"/>  A similar result holds for Hermitian centrosymmetric and skew-centrosymmetric matrices.<ref name=\"simax1\">{{cite journal | last = Yasuda | first = M. | title = A Spectral Characterization of Hermitian Centrosymmetric and Hermitian Skew-Centrosymmetric K-Matrices | journal = SIAM J. Matrix Anal. Appl. | volume = 25 | issue = 3 | pages = 601\u2013605 | year = 2003 | doi = 10.1137/S0895479802418835}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|first=Thomas|last=Muir|author-link=Thomas Muir (mathematician)|year=1960|title=A Treatise on the Theory of Determinants|url=https://archive.org/details/treatiseontheory0000muir|url-access=registration|publisher=Dover|page=[https://archive.org/details/treatiseontheory0000muir/page/19 19]|isbn= 0-486-60670-8}}\n* {{cite journal|doi=10.2307/2323222|first=J. R. |last=Weaver|title= Centrosymmetric (cross-symmetric) matrices, their basic properties, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors|journal=American Mathematical Monthly|volume=92|issue=10|year=1985|pages=711\u2013717|jstor=2323222 }}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://mathworld.wolfram.com/CentrosymmetricMatrix.html Centrosymmetric matrix] on [[MathWorld]].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Centrosymmetric Matrix}}\n[[Category:Linear algebra]]\n[[Category:Matrices]]\n", "name_user": "Myasuda", "label": "safe", "comment": "full author names", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centrosymmetric_matrix"}
{"title_page": "Blueberry Faygo", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Lil Mosey}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Blueberry Faygo\n| type       = single\n| cover      = Lil Mosey - Blueberry Faygo.png\n| artist     = [[Lil Mosey]]\n| album      = [[Certified Hitmaker|Certified Hitmaker (reissue)]]\n| released   = {{start date|2020|2|7|mf=y}}\n| recorded   =\n| format     = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| genre      =\n| length     = {{duration|m=2|s=43}}\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|Mogul Vision}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|[[Lil Mosey|Lathan Echols]]|[[Johnny Gill|Johnny Gill, Jr.]]|[[L.A. Reid|Antonio Reid]]|[[Babyface (musician)|Kenneth Edmonds]]|Callan Wong}}\n| producer   = Callan\n| chronology = [[Lil Mosey]]\n| prev_title = [[Stuck in a Dream]]\n| prev_year  = 2019\n| title      = Blueberry Faygo\n| year       = 2020\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|V_jHc_n0p9c|\"Blueberry Faygo\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Blueberry Faygo'''\" is a single by American rapper [[Lil Mosey]]. It was released on February 7, 2020, by [[Interscope Records]] and Mogul Vision Music. It was released concurrently with the reissue of his second [[studio album]] ''[[Certified Hitmaker]]'' (2019), which the single appears on.<ref>https://listen.tidal.com/album/131891266/credits</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn late 2019, a leaked upload of the track on [[Spotify]] reached 21 million streams before it was taken down.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-945083/|title='We Can't Stop These Kids At All': The Curious Case of a Leaked Hit|last=Leight|first=Elias|date=2020-02-04|website=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It was followed by numerous others, causing the song to go viral before it was officially released on February 7, 2020.<ref name=\"DX\">{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.54469/title.lil-mosey-gets-a-head-start-on-summer-2020-with-blueberry-faygo-single|title=Lil Mosey Gets A Head Start On Summer 2020 With 'Blueberry Faygo' Single|last=|first=|date=2020-02-08|website=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It became Lil Mosey's most successful single to date after being picked up by [[TikTok]] users for dance challenges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elitedaily.com/p/12-viral-tiktok-songs-youll-never-ever-get-sick-of-listening-to-22414496|title=12 Songs That Went Viral On TikTok, Because They Never, Ever Get Old|website=[[Elite Daily]]|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref>\n\n\"Blueberry Faygo\" was produced by Callan and samples \"[[My, My, My (Johnny Gill song)|My, My, My]]\" by American singer-songwriter [[Johnny Gill]].<ref name=\"DX\" />\n\n==Music video==\nThe song's official music video was released on March 26, 2020.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lil Mosey - Blueberry Faygo (Dir. by @_ColeBennett_)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V_jHc_n0p9c|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref> It was released through music video director, [[Cole Bennett]]'s YouTube channel. The video features appearances from Australian rapper [[The Kid Laroi]] and [[TikTok]] stars [[Addison Rae]] & Lil Huddy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/9343752/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-video|title=Lil Mosey&#39;s &#39;Blueberry Faygo&#39; Video: Watch|date=2020-03-26|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\nThe music video was filmed at the Hype House, a TikTok mansion in Los Angeles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2020/03/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo|title=Watch Lil Mosey's \"Blueberry Faygo\" Video|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n\n==Chart performance==\n\"Blueberry Faygo\" debuted at number 62 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], tying with Mosey's previous single \"[[Stuck in a Dream]]\", his highest-charting single before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/lyrics/8551828/lil-mosey-blueberry-faygo-lyrics|title=Lil Mosey's 'Blueberry Faygo' Lyrics|date=2020-02-24|website=Billboard|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> It later surpassed \"Stuck in a Dream\", peaking at number 18, becoming Mosey's first top 20. \n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| 17\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|37|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 16, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders Tip|2|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|11|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 17, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canada|8|artist=Lil Mosey|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|17|year=2020|week=15|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=14&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 14, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| 19\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Estonia ([[Eesti Tipp-40]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ekspress.delfi.ee/areen/eesti-tipp-40-muusikas-sel-nadalal-paugutab-tradattack?id=89544845|title=Eesti Tipp-40 Muusikas: Sel n\u00e4dalal paugutab Trad.Attack!|language=Estonian|last=Nestor|first=Siim|website=[[Eesti Ekspress]]|date=April 14, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|16|artist=Lil Mosey|song=Blueberry Faygo|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|